§IL populi. As in Gaul tribal names appear chiefly in Spain in early times, and the towns known are few. The per- manence of these tribal names in Gaul is shown by their out- living the Roman designations of the towns, and lasting on in so many of the present names.

P, 98 5 12. castulonensem. This was afterwards the boundary between Tarraconensis and Boetiea. Its city Castulo, now Cazlona, which Livy calls urbem validam ac nobilem, gained its importance from its silver mines, and was so Car- thaginian in its sympathies that Hannibal took from it a wife, xxxv. 41. 6. Castulo in Phoenician=‘god's bow,' Schroder.
